included.description: Objective was to research individual's perceptions in dealing with food waste and to design a solution that would reduce levels of food waste going landfills. Research comprised of literary review, surveys, interviews and contextual inquiries methods were used to evaluate peopleâs perceptions of donating and/or composting food. We developed user personas, goals, and tasks to define prototype design requirements. Final deliverable was two prototypes: 1) mobile app to help users identify expiring food items and to locate recycling/donation depots 2) portable refrigeration unit to hold expired or expiring foods for either composting or donating purposes. Usability tests were conducted on both prototypes in a mock kitchen setting to gain contextual insights.
included.title: The Food Waste Solution - Recycle Ben

included.description:
1st Place Judge's award at the 2014 HCDE Capstone and Research Showcase.

For our final project, our team sought to understand what is challenging about learning a smartphone. 

When talking to the HTC research team, we found that the issue was not a lack of understanding of what content was challenging, but the context under which they learn. After doing initial interviews with 5 novice smartphone users to understand how they preferred learning their smartphone, we gained the insight that people actually learning from other people rather than via any other method. 

To further understand the problem space, we held guided co-discovery with 11 participants. We paired novice smartphone users with experienced users and watched their interactions. To best emulate the in-person, knowledge-sharing experience, we decided that a collaborative screen sharing solution would be the most effective and useful for both novice and experienced users alike.
included.title: HTC: Mobile Phone Learning
